  "answer": "## Answer\nCommon failure modes in multi-agent systems cluster around orchestration, role assignment, state tracking, and judging whether a coordinated outcome is actually correct. Framework docs emphasize that multi-agent setups add routing and context-management burden, while empirical work shows that collaboration can still fail because agents lose track of task state or hallucinate about it. ([docs.langchain.com](https://docs.langchain.com/oss/python/langchain/multi-agent/index?utm_source=openai))\n\n**Required aspect coverage**\n- **coordination overhead** — Multi-agent systems need routing, state management, and subagent selection, which adds orchestration cost and complexity. ([docs.langchain.com](https://docs.langchain.com/oss/python/langchain/multi-agent/index?utm_source=openai))\n- **role confusion** — When tasks are split across specialists, systems can struggle to choose the right agent/tool or keep responsibilities cleanly separated. ([docs.langchain.com](https://docs.langchain.com/oss/python/langchain/multi-agent/index?utm_source=openai))\n- **error propagation** — Mistakes in task state, long-horizon context, or hallucinated beliefs can cascade through later agent steps. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.10701?utm_source=openai))\n- **consensus without correctness** — Agents may appear aligned or cooperative while still failing the underlying objective; cooperation can be weak even when helping is inexpensive. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.03903?utm_source=openai))\n- **evaluation difficulty** — Long-running, stateful agent workflows are hard to debug and evaluate, and benchmark results still leave room for improvement in coordination reasoning. ([docs.langchain.com](https://docs.langchain.com/langgraph?utm_source=openai))\n\n## Sources\n- LangChain Multi-agent docs: https://docs.langchain.com/oss/python/langchain/multi-agent/index\n- LangGraph overview: https://docs.langchain.com/langgraph\n- Theory of Mind for Multi-Agent Collaboration via Large Language Models: https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.10701\n- More Capable, Less Cooperative? When LLMs Fail At Zero-Cost Collaboration: https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.07821\n\n## Limitations\nThe evidence is sufficient for the five required aspects, but two labels are inferential rather than verbatim source terms: **role confusion** and **consensus without correctness**. The sources clearly support the underlying phenomena, yet they do not always use those exact phrases. The answer is also weighted toward LLM-based multi-agent systems, so it may underrepresent other multi-agent paradigms."
